social_posts.post_text: Stockings are hung. ✨❤️ Do you have stockings? And if so, where do you hang yours? 🎄 We have a mantle, but I started hanging ours on our stair railing before we got the mantle, so they’ve just stayed! I added the pine and eucalyptus garlands on the stairs this year and love the layered look! ❤️ I felt like I needed to do something on both ends to fill it out and kind of end cap it, because it wasn’t quite reaching the top of the railing. So I grabbed some tree fillers laying nearby and started messing with them until they looked right. And here’s the gentle reminder I have for you: I used what I had. And have had for several years. As much as the Christmas home decor accounts I follow inspire me but also make me want to click add to cart with all the pretty, new, more modern Christmas decor out there…. It’s good that you and I both know and are reminded this time of year: we don’t need new. We don’t have to have our homes decorated exactly like the home decor accounts we see little flashes of on here. We can (and should) be content with the good gifts God’s already given us. Christ himself and salvation from sin being our greatest need and greatest gift we FREELY receive through Christ for those who trust in Him. We can use what we have and be resourceful. Coming from a gal who is quick to add to cart instead of diy or figure out something I can recreate with at home already. 😂 As we decorate our homes for Christmas, let’s be quick to see the kind and good provision from God and be good stewards of the good gifts He’s already given us.❤️

The last year looked a lot like this - little moments that make up the majority of where we spend our lives- the ordinary. God used ordinary moments over and over and over again this past year to teach me what it means to put into a daily, habitual practice of putting Jesus first, and then actually living like that beautiful truth of who Jesus is, is true. In good times, in hard times, in seasons of mourning and loss, in moments of celebrating and joy, putting Jesus first in all circumstances has been the repeated lesson God has been teaching me over the last year, and I am so thankful. He deserves to have the first place in our lives, because that is quite literally who Jesus is- preeminent, having all-supremacy, being all-sufficient in every way. He is worthy. It has been one of my prayers for all of you as I have spent the better part of the last year (and then some!) writing a devotional all about this lesson God’s been teaching me to put Jesus first and live like that’s true. That you would grow in the wisdom and knowledge of Jesus more and more, and that you would see the surpassing worth of Jesus as you grow to know Him more through God’s Word. And that you’d apply that beautiful truth of who Jesus is daily in the mundane, little (and big), ordinary moments that make up your next year, that make up a lifetime. Praying you would keep on (or take next steps!) to put Jesus first in your life this new year, and always, friends. 🤍 Happy new year to you! Here’s my prayer to each of you for this new year, straight from God’s Word in Colossians! 

And so, from the day we heard, we have not ceased to pray for you, asking that you may be filled with the knowledge of his will in all spiritual wisdom and understanding, so as to walk in a manner worthy of the Lord, fully pleasing to him: bearing fruit in every good work and increasing in the knowledge of God; being strengthened with all power, according to his glorious might, for all endurance and patience with joy; giving thanks to the Father, who has qualified you to share in the inheritance of the saints in light.

So it’s mid-February. And maybe you haven’t started off this new year strong. Maybe you feel like you’re figuratively (or quite literally) limping into this new year still. I’m here to remind you, that’s okay. 

You see, living the Christian life and saying yes to Jesus, to trusting in Him and following Him, does not guarantee a life of health, wealth, and prosperity. 

Quite the opposite, the call to take up our cross and follow Jesus will, at times, look like a life that will undoubtedly have suffering in it. Suffering is a very normal part of living the Christian life (Luke 9:23). And we should keep normalizing that. 

But even in our suffering, it is Jesus alone who offers us a safe place to land, who is our comfort and our joy, even in the midst of that suffering. The one who calms the waves with just a word. Jesus is our source of contentment and peace even when everything around us tells us that we should be discontent and anxious because our circumstances aren’t just so. 

Jesus can identify with us in everything, because he endured everything (and more) we might experience in this life, including suffering. He knows. He understands. Not some far off god, but the one True God, who is immanent- near, involved in the lives of his people, able to sympathize with us in every respect, because He himself was tempted in every way we are but never sinned (Hebrews 4:15), therefore he understands, he’s walked the same road on our behalf, and more.

The suffering, servant King, suffered the greatest suffering for us, and then defeated it. Once for all (Romans
6:10).

So while we face suffering of various kinds in this life, we can lift up our heads to heaven like Job did when everything was taken from him and still say: “He is good”. Even when our circumstances aren’t “good”. . Even when we’re barely staying afloat. We suffer, but not without hope (1 Thess. 4:13). Because of Jesus. Because of the resurrection and the promise of hope it offers for all those who trust in Jesus.

Keep putting Jesus first, friends. Fight for delight. Jesus is our life raft to stay afloat. So keep on putting Him first. He is so worthy. He is where the joy is, even now.

A prayer for the week ahead on praying and abiding:

So as you are the vine and we are the branches, please help us to abide in you this week by the power of the Holy Spirit and by your Word that we might bear much fruit this week in whatever it is you already have planned for us. Lord, give us more of a desire to be more devoted in our communication with you through prayer (Colossians 4:2) and that we would seek to speak with you first and unceasingly no matter what the week ahead holds (1 Thess. 5:14). Lord, these two verses from your Word command us to pray, out of love for you. Help us to not grow apathetic of praying to you, especially in easier seasons when things are going “good”, everything is “perfect”, and we inevitably feel we have little need. Help us Jesus to not grow forgetful or lazy to communicate with you and intercede for others by bringing you their petitions and requests before you on their behalf. Jesus, help us to know and love you more this week than we did last week and let our habits of prayer and time spent in your Word reflect that. Amen. 💗

The Christian life, following Jesus, does not mean a life free from difficulties, hardship, or suffering. The Bible would argue against that explicitly, Jesus himself articulating the cost of following Him in Luke 9 along with other places in the Word. But it does mean that we have an enduring and eternal hope in Jesus as we walk through those things in life when they arise. Not fleeting happiness that changes at the whim based on our circumstances or feelings. Jesus is our true hope. True joy. True assurance. In this life and even in death. That is the power of the resurrection, which we look forward to celebrating this Easter, and always. Follow Jesus. He is worthy. 💗

Okay - I have become so passionate about building Easter memories with your families ever since a sweet woman from my church discipled ME and took time to share SO many fantastic ways to build memories surrounding Easter that are all excellent discipleship tools to prepare our hearts for celebrating Resurrection Sunday. One thing she always shares in her presentations every time she hosts one at our church is: “do something, but don’t try to do everything.” I have always loved this wise counsel, knowing myself and always wanting to do ALL the things, but when we do that we get stressed and it becomes more about that other thing and less about the object of our faith- Jesus. 💗 Some of these I’ve taken from her, some of these have become our own that work best for US. These are just a few ways you could start OR add to any Easter memories within your own home. Do something, but don’t try to do everything. 💗 Especially if you have little littles! Praying these encourage you to prepare your family’s (and your own!) hearts for Easter. 

✨EASTER FELT BOARD ACTIVITY - Starts 2 weeks before Easter, have this saved to my blog.
✨READ A STORY EACH DAY FROM YOUR FAV STORYBOOK BIBLE - Start counting back from the resurrection story 2 weeks to 1 month (whichever you prefer!). Read one story each day leading up to Easter, finishing reading the resurrection on Easter morning. 
✨READ THE PROMISED HOPE - our favs @readkaleidoscope, this volume through Luke has 25 chapters, read one chapter each day leading up to Easter, finishing the last chapter on Easter morning! 
✨RESURRECTION EGGS - Start 2 weeks to 1 month before, we pull these out a few times leading up to Easter and after the kids find all the eggs, we open one egg at a time and read the verse or walk through the Easter story in one of our storybook bibles that goes with that egg. You can make your own or find them already assembled online a lot of places!
✨RESURRECTION CARDS - start 2 weeks before Easter from @pipandjpapery. Each card has a key verse to read, prophecies from OT fulfilled in Jesus, verses to meditate on, prayer prompt, and hymn to learn and sing together each night after reading your card.

Our aim in reading our bibles or praying or any of the spiritual disciplines that we see in scripture is for the purpose of godliness. Christlikeness. Growing in our knowledge and love for God and in turn growing in maturity. For our good and His glory. We as Christians are called to work at these things, but when our purpose in pursuing them is not for the purpose of godliness, they become a drudgery, not a delight. Christ himself is our greatest example of someone who did this perfectly. He is the substance in our Bible reading, our praying, our serving or fasting or evangelizing, or whichever spiritual discipline it might be. So friend, keep putting Him first as you work at the spiritual disciplines daily, knowing that God expects us to, but also that they are a means that God uses to grow us in Christian maturity for our good and for His glory. 🤍

The enemy loves to isolate.
The enemy loves to twist God’s words.
The enemy loves to confuse.
The enemy loves to justify sin. 
The enemy loves to kill and destroy.
(See Genesis 3 for some first accounts of that).

But for those who are in Christ:

We suffer, but not without hope. We battle temptation and sin, knowing full well that for those who are His are being sanctified until The Day. 

The Day when Christ returns- bringing eternal glory to those who are His and eternal judgement on those who have rejected Him. 

Sin & Satan will not have the final say. Satan’s time waging war here on earth is limited. Satan himself has to be given permission to tempt and test the saints- See Jesus when he was tempted for 40 days in the wilderness in Luke 4 and the story of Job in Job 1. This was not because God does not love His Son or Job. Or you or me. In allowing Satan to tempt and test, God used both of those instances to shame the devil. To prove that God does, and will always, have the final say. 

Evil is limited. Satan has a finite amount of time. Unlike God who is limitless and infinite. 

And so, One day, all will be made right. One day, no more sin. One day, no more tears, suffering, death, physical or mental illness. One day, only glory. One day, all things made new. One day, the light of the world who lights up the darkness here and now will be our very light, no need for the sun at all- God’s glory forever our lamp (Rev. 21:23). 

Press on, saint. Wage war against your own sin. Do not let it rule over you. And while you do so, remember that evil and the enemy is limited. Encourage and remind one another of the hope you have as an anchor of your soul as long as it’s called today (Hebrews 3:13). And this life, broken and battered by sin that makes us toil, pray in agony as Jesus did on the Mount of Olives… that makes us weary and teary… is just a vapor. Eternity awaits those who share in His suffering and in His resurrection. 

So as we suffer and grieve in this life for many reasons, remember that in life and in death, we have an eternal hope in Jesus who will carry us all the way home, to that blessed shore. You and I, we’re almost home. Praise the Lord. 💗

The God who is more than enough. The all-sufficient one. God almighty. El Shaddai. Jesus. Set his face to go to Jerusalem. 🌿

What are some things you notice when you read this same verse, in a few different versions? All saying the same thing ultimately, but mildly different at the same time. Reading Luke 9:51 for women’s Bible study a few weeks ago really caused me to pause and consider what Jesus felt, what Jesus knew, and how Jesus responded to the Father’s will at this moment. 

When it was time for the beginning of the end of Jesus’s earthly ministry, when he would set out to fulfill what man could not do, when it came time for the Son of Man to suffer, to be mocked and spit on and beaten, to be crucified for the sins He never committed, to be separated from the Father, so that He would fulfill the Father’s plan to send the Son to be the savior of the world…

He set his face towards Jerusalem. 

Knowing full well what was to come being totally God who knows all things while at the very same time being totally man, who would later pray in agony to the Father that if it was possible for this cup, the cup of God’s wrath, to be taken away from Him, to do it. 

And yet, He understood. He knew what was required of Him in order to save sinners. 

So he steadfastly set his face towards Jerusalem. 

Resolved. Determined.

Set your face to the Son as we enter Holy Week together, friend. 🤍🌿

On Monday of Holy Week (yesterday), we read in Mark 11:12-19 Jesus cursing the fig tree & cleansing the temple. Both significant events that should cause us to pause & consider what they teach us about Jesus. *swipe to read more on an article I read that was so helpful in adding rich historical context and understanding on Jesus cleansing the temple*

Today, a story much different, completely opposite in fact, from that which we read about the day before when we see how the widow gives everything she has to God in the offering box while Jesus is teaching in the temple (Mark 12:41-44). It’s the story of Judas betraying Jesus. Two days before the Passover and Feast of Unleavened Bread. Satan enters into Judas (Luke 22:3), and he sets out to betray the single-most faithful friend he would ever have a relationship with. The single-most faithful friend we still have the gift of having a relationship with today, who we also call Savior and Lord, Jesus Christ.
 
Remember the worthiness of Jesus today as you read the story of Judas betraying him for nothing, 30 pieces of silver (Mark 14:1-10, Luke 22:1-6). Remember the debt that stood against you and me that he paid for, a debt that we could never repay on our own. Remember who He is, matchless in worth and preeminent above all things. Surpassingly worthy. Worthy of all of our praise, worship, and offerings. Read Colossians 1:15-23. 🤍

Thursday 🥖🍷🙏🏼🐓

-Jesus sends Peter & John to prepare for the First Day of Unleavened Bread & the Passover (Mark 14:12-15, Luke 22:1-2, read also Exodus 11-15 for the history of how the Passover celebration came to be).

-Jesus washes the disciples feet (John 13:1-20), celebrates his last Passover on earth with the disciples, established the Lord’s Supper, also known as communion today, foretells Peter’s denial, prepares them for trouble ahead, and prays in agony to the Father in the garden at the Mount of Olives (Gethsemane) as he himself prepares for what he must do soon. (Mark 22:14-46)

In all of these accounts, we see Jesus, totally God and totally man, humbly love and serve and continue to prepare their hearts for what is to come, knowing full-well that when the Good Shepherd is stricken, all his sheep will scatter. He never stops serving and loving his 12 closest friends, the disciples, even when he knows in just a short while, they will abandon him and deny ever knowing him after 1 of the 12 betrays him for next to nothing, 30 pieces of silver. (Mark 22:14-62)

-After praying in agony in the garden, Jesus is betrayed by Judas and taken away by the mob from the chief priests, scribes, and elders to the Sanhedrin, the Jewish authorities made up of 70 men who included the elders and high priest, where they would seek any way possible to convict him of a charge, put on a sham trial, and falsely convict him, before finally convicting him on the charge of blasphemy, which was belittling the name of God or treat him with contempt. (Mark 14:53-65)

-As Jesus is being falsely accused, spit on, blindfolded, beaten, and mocked, Peter is nearby in a courtyard outside, where he would be approached 3 times for knowing Jesus, and 3 times would deny His beloved friend and Savior, Jesus before the rooster crows. (Mark 14:65-72). 

The King of Kings and Lord of Lords, the Son of Man, did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give His life as a ransom for many (Mark 10:41-45). He knew this. He understood this. He alone could fulfill this. And He would do so humbly and faithfully as He carried out the Father’s plan to save sinners. 

We remember this today.

Sunday afternoon reset before the week ahead.🌷Just a snapshot of some of the ways I like to prepare for the upcoming week. In our current season, our home is the place where both Dakota and I work, and also where our children “go” to school. We do a lot of living and learning and growing within the walls of this home. Not every Sunday looks like this or must be followed in a rigid, inflexible way, but a general clean and pick up in the remaining quiet before rest time after church is done has been so helpful to serve my family in this way. Yes it means that my sitting and “quiet time” is limited, but these are some simple ways I can sabbath while serving my family and the Lord as I steward the place He’s given us to call home. Practicing the gospel as I bring order back into our space. Living in light of who Jesus is and the good order God gives in a world of disorder and confusion: this is a beautiful reminder that all things, when done with the correct heart posture and heart motive, can be an act of worship to God. I do love a clean and organized home. I sincerely do focus on work and teaching better in a home that is clean. But I have to remind myself often that having a clean home isn’t about me. And it’s also not about having a tidy, insta-worthy home to snap a photo or 10 second reel, because that’s just a form of people pleasing, which at the core is a form of pride, a sin. Trust me, ask me how I know. No, much more than that, it’s about worshipping the finished work of God through His one and only Son by the power of the Holy Spirit, and living that good news out in our homes. Bringing chaos into order. Reflecting Christ in the mundane. Pointing those in my home to the One whose finished work and resurrection gives those who trust in him a living, eternal hope that we can walk in now… knowing it is He alone who holds all things together, even when the Sunday reset doesn’t measure up to all I wanted it to be or accomplish. This is the true reset my heart needs each Sunday.🌷 Also, always yes to homemade whipped cream and strawbs 🍓

This season of life requires more focus in the margins and more grace to designate most of that “extra” work in the margins, too. This can be difficult for me sometimes. 😅 Maybe you can relate?

Like, how I want to get that thing done when I want to get it done and how dare anyone need me to open their applesauce pouch for them before I’ve completed cleaning this toilet. Or the moment I sit down to write out a thought for a potential book idea, I’m quickly interrupted by a need in front of me. And the thought is gone… immediately. Sigh. 

And yet… for as much as I love a clean and orderly home, I’m learning that a joyful, cheerful mom with messes to tend to later in the margins is better than a joyless mom with an immaculate home. 

I’m learning that a present mom, enjoying her children and seeking to meet their needs when they’re right in front of her is better than a distracted mom, not enjoying her children and their presence because she “must” do this email or reply to this DM right now. 

I’m learning that, like Paul said in his letter to the Philippians, contentment is learned over time, a lifetime, and the secret to all of it is Christ himself (Phil. 4:11-13). He’s the substance (Colossians 2:17). He’s the One we find true and everlasting contentment in. 

There are times when the work must be done and is necessary to complete by a certain time, but more often than not in my case, the task or email or reply can wait for the margins (or I just need to make better use of the margins God’s giving me).

This is a dying to self in a tangible way. A model for our children and those within our home of the love of Christ and resting in His sufficiency.

I’m learning that the priority work and the work in the margins work together best when my heart is prioritizing Jesus above all things. Re-orienting. Re-ordering. For the better. Because it allows Him to do the necessary work in ME.

And I trust that He who began a good work in me WILL bring it to completion (Phil. 1:6). He’ll keep using all of these humbling moments, & even suffering, to mature me and continually shape and mold me more into the image of Himself, Christ. From one degree of glory to another. 🤍

Here’s a simple and fun art project you can try with your kiddos (at home or classroom!) to connect and create together! Now that leaf colors are in full force and beginning to fall. It’s amazing that in the 3 days my husband and I (and Landyn!) were gone at TGC23, the leaves really changed and are dropping a ton! 

To create:
1. Go out and collect leaves together. 
2. Arrange leaves in middle of sticky side of press n seal paper.
3. Place another sheet of press n seal over arranged leaves (sticky side down on top of leaves).
4. Trace a shape of a leaf on construction paper, puncture hole in middle of leaf and cut around leaf on the inside part of the leaf to create a frame.
5. Place frame on one side of the press n seal that showcases the front or top of the leaves.
6. Staple frame onto press n seal paper.

Done! It’s so simple and they decorate your home or classroom so beautifully even after the leaves have fallen and turn brown (for us that can happen so quickly if we get a windy day!)

An abbreviated excerpt from an advent devotional I shared at the start of December to a group of women in my community: 

Advent (arrival), namely the arrival of Jesus Christ, is important in many ways.

First, in the midst of the hustle and bustle and jingle bells, Advent is a challenge for us to focus on Jesus in the weeks leading up to Christmas. Advent invites us to remember the hope, peace, joy, and love that Jesus offers. 

Second, Advent builds anticipation. 
Micah 5:4-5 says: 
He will stand and shepherd them
in the strength of the Lord,
in the majestic name of the Lord his God.
They will live securely,
for then his greatness will extend
to the ends of the earth.
5 He will be their peace.

The prophet Micah gave this prophecy from God to the people of Israel of the conquering King Jesus to come around 700 years before his birth in Bethlehem. From the time the last prophet of the OT, Malachi, prophesied Jesus’s coming birth, there was a 400 year gap. This gap- it seemed as though hope was decreasing and it seemed like silence from God was increasing. But even in the silence, God is still working. It appeared that during this time, God was absent, but He wasn’t. God was with them. And God’s people held onto the hope that God would be faithful to keep his promises, as he had proven to do already over and over again over the course of their history. 

As we think about this long-awaited good news the prophets gave predicting Jesus’s birth, we are thankful for the hope of Jesus. During advent, we anticipate celebrating Jesus’s first coming. But, Advent also points us to His second coming. Even today, we feel it, don’t we? We are still longing for hope, peace, joy, and rest in a weary world. We long to rejoice in that new and glorious morn’ once and for all. We long for the final morning when Emmanuel will forever be our light: Revelation 21:23 “need no sun or the moon to shine on it, because the glory of God illuminates it, and its lamp is the Lamb”. 

While we wait for the second advent, we wait with hope and with peace EVEN in the midst of suffering, loss, and difficult or unexpected circumstances. Praying Jesus  encourages your heart this Christmas Eve. ❤️

Merry Christmas from us to you all, friends! 🎄 Because of Jesus, we have lasting reason to celebrate His first coming and His second advent, His second coming! The King of Kings and Lord of Lords laid his glory down to be brought low, so that we too might be raised up with him, redeemed through His life, death, and resurrection! What a gift! This is the hope and peace we have in Christ! Praying you’d be most grateful for this inexpressible gift from God today and always. ❤️

When my heart is postured at serving the Lord and my family by turning over the kitchen, everything changes internally for me. What once was a grumbly, entitled wife and mom bringing order to the chaos, is now an eternity-mindset wife and mom who aims to worship Jesus even in these mundane moments of bringing order to the chaos of a messy kitchen. 

This habit - a heart focused on Jesus as I turn over the kitchen daily, and “putting the kitchen to bed” nightly, and in all the mundane duties I have been given to do as a wife and mom, is a habit I am keeping from 2023 and bringing into 2024… and when I fail and forget, or simply just leave the dishes for the next day… I am praying I would have a humble heart, quickly ready to fall back into the posture of being here to serve, not be served, just like my Savior, Jesus. Lord, help me in 2024!✨

I had big plans for this week. Writing, serving, hosting, indoor park-ing…. And yet. This was not what God had for me this week. The January sickness struck our house yet again, you too? 

So this week, instead of writing ✍🏼:

I got to let God write His Word on my heart and in my mind and share that truth over and over again to my little ones not feeling well… and if I’m being honest, was just as much of a necessary reminder for me too. 

This week, instead of being able to go serve a local ministry in my community 🏡:

I got to serve my neighbors right within the walls of my own home, my ministry first and foremost. 

This week, instead of gathering and meeting and playing 📅 🛝:

I got to slow down and meet as a family over and over again as we came alongside one another in our lack, weakness, sickness, and struggles. 

And it’s okay. While I’m very much still learning and growing, I understand that it is Christ IN me, my union with Him, that gives me peace, hope, and joy no matter my circumstances. When the world tells me otherwise, I will remember that this selfless and humble posture, taking the lower seat, seeking to serve and not be served… the laying down of my needs, wants, time, plans for someone else’s greater good, it is a worthy thing. A godly thing. A Christ-likeness thing. A good thing. And not just a good thing for the other person, but for me too. It changes the heart, not necessarily the circumstance. It’s good to remember that. 

I’m learning that wherever right now is, whatever circumstances the Lord places me in, to be all in for His glory and not my own as I trust in Him completely to carry me through and lead the way. Fleshing out the gospel really is a dying of self, of sharing and taking on the burdens of those around us, and seeking to restore and redeem what’s broken. It looked like this, this week. 🤍

Surely God is my help; the Lord is the one who sustains me. Psalm 54:4 🤍
